material has been shown to be a
promising and highly conducting electrolyte material. For
= 0.150 we have been able to stabilize a
cubic phase with the optimum proportion of charge carriers and
vacancies in the face sharing tetrahedral-octahedral channels for
Li-conduction. Higher substituting levels decrease the con-
ductivity due to the blocking eﬀect of the Ga in tetrahedral
position to the Li conduction path. Moreover, we have proven
an optimum method for Li-conducting ceramic processing
that leads to high density ceramic materials. EIS
data have shown Li-ion conductivities as high as 1.3 mS cm
MAS NMR measurements have been shown to be crucial to
better understand the eﬀect of protonation on the sintering of
these LZLGO materials. It has also been used to conﬁrm the
tetrahedral location of the substituting Ga in the garnet
structure and to understand the substitution eﬀect in this series.
